The domain is described by a set of variables f ∈ F which can assume values from a (finite) domain D(f) ⊆ N. A state is given by the particular assignment of values to these variables: S = {f = v | v ∈ D(f) ∀f ∈ F}. The value of variable f in state S is referred to as S(f). The action model A consists of operators a = 〈Ca, Ea〉 where Ca is the cost of the action, and Ea = {〈f, vo, vn〉 | f ∈ F ; vo, vn ∈ {−1} ∪D(f)} is the set of effects. The transition function δ(·) determines the next state after the application of action a to state S as -
δ(a,S) = ⊥ if ∃〈f, vo, vn〉 ∈ Ea s.t. vo 6= −1 ∧ vo 6= S(f);
= {f = vn∀〈f, vo, vn〉 ∈ Ea; else f = S(f)} otherwise.
